@victoriayue   I'll need some additional information to help you.

* What computer hardware you are using and the OS version?
* Please post the full `ludwig train ....` command issued
* Please post the `config.yaml` describing the model
* Please post the full run log where the error occurs.
* Please post output from `pip list` command.

I'm getting the same issue when I try to run the [mnist](https://github.com/ludwig-ai/ludwig/tree/master/examples/mnist) example. I've run the following commands

```
pip3 install ludwig
git clone https://github.com/ludwig-ai/ludwig.git
cd ludwig/examples/mnist/
python3 simple_model_training.py
```
I get the following error traceback:
```
~/mnist Â» python3 simple_model_training.py
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "/Users/zhumich/mnist/simple_model_training.py", line 13, in <module>
    from ludwig.api import LudwigModel
  File "/Library/Frameworks/Python.framework/Versions/3.9/lib/python3.9/site-packages/ludwig/__init__.py", line 16, in <module>
    from ludwig.api import LudwigModel
  File "/Library/Frameworks/Python.framework/Versions/3.9/lib/python3.9/site-packages/ludwig/api.py", line 39, in <module>

  File "/Library/Frameworks/Python.framework/Versions/3.9/lib/python3.9/site-packages/ludwig/data/postprocessing.py", line 19, in <module>
    from ludwig.features.feature_registries import output_type_registry
  File "/Library/Frameworks/Python.framework/Versions/3.9/lib/python3.9/site-packages/ludwig/features/feature_registries.py", line 25, in <module>
    from ludwig.features.bag_feature import BagBaseFeature
  File "/Library/Frameworks/Python.framework/Versions/3.9/lib/python3.9/site-packages/ludwig/features/bag_feature.py", line 24, in <module>
    from ludwig.features.base_feature import BaseFeature
  File "/Library/Frameworks/Python.framework/Versions/3.9/lib/python3.9/site-packages/ludwig/features/base_feature.py", line 21, in <module>
    from ludwig.models.modules.recurrent_modules import reduce_sequence
  File "/Library/Frameworks/Python.framework/Versions/3.9/lib/python3.9/site-packages/ludwig/models/modules/recurrent_modules.py", line 20, in <module>
    from tensorflow.contrib.rnn import MultiRNNCell, LSTMStateTuple
ModuleNotFoundError: No module named 'tensorflow.contrib'
```

It seems like the issue may be because `tensorflow.contrib` only existed in tensorflow v1 and not v2 according to this [post](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/55082483/why-can-i-not-import-tensorflow-contrib-i-get-an-error-of-no-module-named-tenso) and this [post](https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/issues/28216).



**Environment:**
- OS: MacOS 11.3.1
- Python version: 3.9.5
- Ludwig version 0.4

I have the same issue on a new Ubuntu 20.04 installation. Got Python 3.9 and ludwig 0.4.
Tried with tensorflow 2.6 and 2.5.1
It worked 3 weeks ago using tf 2.4.1 on Ubuntu 18.04 with Python 3.8.8. Can't reproduce that setup because though as I replaced it with Ubuntu 20.04..

For some reason `ludwig[serve]` installs ludwig 0.1.0 which should be the cause of this issue.

I got my setup fixed by only installing the required modules "audio" and "dask".

@michaelbzhu  the stack trace you provided imply that you're running a version 0.2.x version of Ludwig, when it was built on top of TF1.x.  The line numbers cited in the stack trace, coincide with Ludwig v0.2.x
```
  File "/Library/Frameworks/Python.framework/Versions/3.9/lib/python3.9/site-packages/ludwig/features/base_feature.py", line 21, in <module>
    from ludwig.models.modules.recurrent_modules import reduce_sequence
  File "/Library/Frameworks/Python.framework/Versions/3.9/lib/python3.9/site-packages/ludwig/models/modules/recurrent_modules.py", line 20, in <module>
    from tensorflow.contrib.rnn import MultiRNNCell, LSTMStateTuple
ModuleNotFoundError: No module named 'tensorflow.contrib'
```

The line numbers in the stack trace do not match code in Ludwig v0.3 and later.  

It appears your software environment may not be correct.

if you run `pip list | grep ludwig` what does it show?  On my laptop, I see this
```
root@8a2c7d7a70eb:/opt/project/examples/mnist# pip list | grep ludwig
ludwig                     0.4                 /app
```

@Peetee06  your observation re: installing ludwig 0.1.0 is consistent with the stack trace observation noted above.  In your case, it appears `pip` is falling back to cached older versions of ludwig.  

@michaelbzhu @Peetee06 @victoriayue   Assuming the software environment you are using is one where you ran older versions of ludwig, I think there are couple options.

**Option 1**  install ludwig 0.4 with `pip install --no-cache-dir ludwig==0.4`.  This should prevent `pip` from searching it's cache.

**Option 2** clean out the local `pip` cache of any older versions of ludwig, look at the `pip cache` command: https://pip.pypa.io/en/stable/cli/pip_cache/

The options are not mutually exclusive,  you can do both.

If these options do not provide a solution, the next step will be to debug your install of ludwig.  For that it will be helpful to post the full output from the `pip install` of ludwig.

I just purged the pip cache using `pip cache purge` and reinstalled ludwig[serve] (as this seems to be the root cause of ludwig[full] failing as well] with `pip install ludwig[serve]`.
